results.notes:
Collected and photographed in situ by Steve Antrobus.
Growing solo under pines. The cap is drab brown with a tinge of gold. Margin isn’t obviously striate, but I suppose the case could be made that there are shallow inconspicuous striations. Stipe is exannulate, white and smooth and terminates within a persistent, if thin, volva. It’s not clear to me whether the stipe is ‘totally elongating’ or bulbous. I’m waiting for the cap to open up a bit and will section the stipe thereafter to get a better vantage point.
Smell is earthy, with a hint of cut potato that I may be imagining.
What’s most remarkable about this mushroom is its size – it’s quite hefty, sturdy too – and its weird combination of morphological traits. The latter quality has me puzzled as to which section this amanita belongs to, let alone which species it represents. My initial thought was sect. Caesareae, with A. murrilliana being a good candidate, but who knows. I’ll section it and take more pictures later. In the meantime, I’d appreciate suggestions.
Spore print: Pluteus-pink.
Micro character: spores are elliptical and often have oil droplet; cheilocystidia sporadically abundant and variously sized and shaped (club-shaped, cylindrical, capitate/umbonate); basidia 4-sterigmate

—

Mirrored on iNaturalist as observation 144178022 on December 11, 2022.

results.notes:
On California bay (Umbellularia californica), where it was common at this location, on the ridge of the Santa Lucia Range above Cayucos.

Thallus thin, greenish. Apothecia purplish (when wet), plane with raised rim to convex with weak or lacking margin. Epihymenium violet, with weak POL+ crystals, hymenium hyaline, hypothecium yellowish, intensifying in K. Paraphyses long and slender, simple to rarely branched near tip, apical cell clavate, hyaline. Exciple lacking algae, POL+ fine white crystals, with enlarged cells on outer edge.

Spores 8 per ascus, not spirally coiled. Ascus clavate, with K/I + solid blue tholus. Size variable, larger ones 65×4, most 14+ septate, fusiform to acicular with one blunt and one pointed end, occasionally with two pointed ends, straight to weakly curved or sigmoid.

See also observation 278496 for another similar observation.
